// TEST: exec_ts_diverging_call_tail
// EXPECT: output "got:42"
// EXPECT: targets ts
//
// Restricted to `ts`: a diverging-intrinsic tail (`unreachable()`/`todo()`) is
// emitted as `return <throw/raise/panic>` by every other backend too (js:
// `return throw …`, python: `return raise …`, go: `panic(...) used as value`) —
// the same shared limitation this TS fix addresses, surfaced as an OPEN. Widen
// to all five once the shared fix lands.
//
// A function whose body *tail* is a diverging intrinsic call (`unreachable()`),
// reached only on a branch the test never takes (the guessing-game cluster).
// `unreachable()`/`todo()` lower to a bare `throw` *statement*, so emitting them
// after `return ` (`return throw new Error(...)`) is invalid TS (`tsc` TS1109).
// The fix emits the diverging tail as a statement, not a `return` operand. The
// program runs the non-diverging path, so the fixture pins valid *syntax*
// (compile-time) without ever executing the `throw`. js/python share the same
// `return raise`/`return throw` hazard; rust/go their analogues.
//
// `main` is intentionally NOT `public` (see hello_world.bock for the Go
// entry-point rationale).
module main

fn checked(n: Int) -> Int {
  if (n >= 0) {
    return n
  }
  // Tail position: a diverging call, never reached for n >= 0.
  unreachable()
}

fn main() -> Void {
  println("got:${checked(42)}")
}
